      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Price of Safety</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Walter Kent says members of Congress calling for investigations and regulation of tire industry should turn their attention to health maintenance organizations, which by their practices probably pose as much public hazard as tire industry</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''More Indications Hazards of Tires Were Long Known'' (Business Day, Sept. 7):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''More Indications Hazards of Tires Were Long Known'' (Business Day, Sept. 7):</p>
        <p>It is interesting how quickly members of both political parties, in both houses of Congress, have called for investigations and regulation of the tire industry. We will all probably be better off for it.</p>
        <p>One would hope that some of this zeal will remain and be directed toward the health maintenance organizations, which by their practices of denial and delay are probably responsible for as much public hazard as the tire industry.</p>
        <p>WALTER KENT  Glen Rock, N.J., Sept. 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
